Today is Friday, the 23rd of September 2011.

5
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:31,000
My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

6
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:40,000
I am in Amherst, Massachusetts on the campus of the University of Massachusetts in New Africa House with John Bishop, our project videographer,

7
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:53,000
to do an oral history for the Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

8
00:00:53,000 --> 00:01:08,000
We are privileged today to be with Dr. William Lamar Strickland, who has taught here for many years and long before that, deep engagement in the movement and the whole host of capacities that we'll discuss today.

9
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Dr. Strickland, it's a pleasure.

10
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:14,000
Bill, Bill.

11
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:28,000
Just a quick note before we dive into the interview, our videographer John Bishop was long personal acquaintance with Worth W. Long and before we turned on, we were chatting a little bit about a mention of Worth.

12
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:32,000
I thought maybe we just asked you to lay that down here so we don't miss it.

13
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:45,000
I assume people know Worth was regarded as the poet of Snick and for some strange reason there's a quote that's been attributed to Stokely, which actually was Worth's quote.

14
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:51,000
And it was quote, false face to America, we have found you out.

15
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:55,000
That's also a work.

16
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:12,000
Bill, let me have you begin today with just recalling your family and your parents and how you just come up in Oxford and how you foundry kind of out of that context, say to Boston one?

17
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Wow.

18
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:38,000
Well, it was elementary school, I had a teacher who thought I should apply to Latin school and Latin school had a procedure where they would let you in based on your grades.

19
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:56,000
And then as you sat in the auditorium, they would tell you look to your left and look to your right because he, because at the time Latin school was all boys, of course, 16, 35, they're not going to be here at the end.

20
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:03,000
So you enter in class six, which is the seventh grade because we had six years of Latin and that was correct.

21
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:14,000
Almost 700 guys started out and we graduated about 22230 of whom six of us were black.

22
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:18,000
What if you were to some recollections of your parents?

23
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:28,000
Well, my father was killed in the war and my mother was worked for Raytheon, she worked for Union for Raytheon's.

24
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:39,000
But I had this, I had aunts in Roxbury and fabulous aunts in Newark, New Jersey and my mother's family was from Georgia.

25
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:44,000
So I was as a child, I would go to visit them in Georgia.

26
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:56,000
In fact, it, a little town, a little town outside of Macon called, called, haddock, Macon.

27
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:10,000
And I later, I later found out, I guess it was my great grandmother was the offspring of a plantation owner.

28
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:17,000
And the, because the town between Macon and haddock was a town called Gray.

29
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:25,000
And this plantation owner was evidently a major figure in Georgia during the Confederacy Madison Gray.

30
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:30,000
And my uncle, my uncle was named after him, Gray.

31
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:45,000
But evidently this was a fairly, I guess, open mind because he left part of his land to my mother's family.

32
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:54,000
So that was the land that they had when I went, when I went as a child to visit them in Georgia.

33
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:57,000
Which branch of service? Marine Corps.

34
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:02,000
Oh, no, he was, I mean, I was in the Marine Corps.

35
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:05,000
He was killed well.

36
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:08,000
Oh, God.

37
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:14,000
I think in the Italian, in the Italian campaign.

38
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:37,000
You've written in certain places about, kind of, part of the family and community world, grew up in Roxbury, and included, I'm a student, through, I think, Malcolm Little.

39
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:50,000
Yes, I just recently wrote about that, tried to, to, we could pitchulate that because there's been a recent biography of Malcolm X X, to which I take great exception.

40
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:57,000
And I wanted to establish that my recollections came from personal experience and not from second-hand experience.

41
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:11,000
Because I met Malcolm X when I was very young, because he was a very good friend of my cousin, whom I say in the article, was my hero, because I would be at my aunt and uncle's house and girls would call him from New York.

42
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:15,000
And I thought that was the coolest thing. It was the coolest, coolest thing.

43
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:25,000
So I wanted to grow up and be exactly like him, the, but they also were part of a group which I, on, on later reflection, I think, may have been,

44
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:34,000
significantly West Indian, because my cousin was, his father was, was, was, was, was, was, was, Barbadian.

45
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:52,000
The uncle Jake, that, that was his name, Jake Edman. and it's, and my relatives claim that at some point in my youth, I said that, that, the uncle Jake, I called uncle Jake, the man too mean to die.

46
00:06:52,000 --> 00:07:00,000
But he was, but he was cool. And, and he was also a numbers banker.

47
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:15,000
And so I grew up with numbers sheets and all around my, and uncle's house. But Leslie got out of the war and he came, he got into a, I don't know what the cause of it was.

48
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:28,000
And so he got into a hassle down at Tremont Street, in fact, I really think it's the same pool room where, where Malcolm X met, met Shorty Jarvis.

49
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:37,000
And so he came home and, and got his pistol and went back and whacked one or more of the people.

50
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:46,000
But because my uncle was in touch with the Irish mafia, he got, Leslie the best criminal defense attorney.

51
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:57,000
So Leslie only got a year and a day eventually. So he was in Charlestown State Prison at the same time as Malcolm X.

52
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:11,000
So when I met Malcolm X later, when Malcolm X came to speak at Harvard, I went, talked, went up after his, after his talk, mentioned Roxbury and, and Leslie.

53
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:15,000
And then we were tight until he died.

54
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:33,000
Yeah, it's a little bit more about, um, the personal history in those years. Um, obviously it was something up a, an usual quite unusual thing still for American, American man to be up through Boston, and in the library.

55
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:40,000
I'm interested in your recollections of moving through those experiences.

56
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:48,000
Well, there may or may not have been a quota, but there were only 11 of us, out of 1000 guys at Harvard.

57
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:58,000
And because of that number, you knew all the black guys who had gone to Harvard 10 years before you were 20 years before you were in 20 years after you.

58
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:06,000
So it was, um, an inform. And then they would, you know, they, they was a little socialization process when you arrived.

59
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:14,000
They would say, well, most of the people whom you will account to here will believe that you're only here for one of two reasons.

60
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:22,000
That you are some made son or that you are a genius in your responsibility is to demonstrate point B.

61
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:32,000
So there was a nurturing, um, group presence in, in, in Cambridge, in Cambridge was.

62
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:52,000
And, and I remember, you know, Harvard, I have very, very fond memories of, of Harvard, Harvard taught, you know, like Dubois, you know, Dubois started writing for newspapers when he was in, uh,

63
00:09:52,000 --> 00:10:00,000
a high school student at Great Barrington. And he, when he got to Harvard, he flunked.

64
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:07,000
I think it was English one. It was introduced because he's to have a compulsory freshman writing class for everyone.

65
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:23,000
And I had been similarly favored in my skipped kindergarten and they wanted me to skip first grade and then done well at Latin school.

66
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:31,000
And the, so when I got into the writing class, I was a little floored with my language.

67
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:47,000
And, uh, we had a English teacher, even Mr. Russo, who said to us, and now young man, I am going to teach you the secret of good writing.

68
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:59,000
The secret of good writing is rewriting. And so I was able to carry that on, to carry that to, uh, to, uh, on to Harvard.

69
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:04,000
But it was, I have very pleasant memories of Cambridge. Yeah.

70
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:11,000
Except when they asked me to put, leave them on my money, leave them on my money in my will.

71
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:14,000
Little money that I have.

72
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:22,000
I had meant to ask earlier. I just want to make sure I'm, I bet it's here. Yeah, your birthday is the fourth of January, nineteen, thirty-seven.

73
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:26,000
So you, and you finished a Boston Latin in...

74
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:28,000
Fifty-four.

75
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:31,000
Fifty-four. Oh, so basically with Brown.

76
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:35,000
What's the name of the Brown? Yeah, I wasn't thinking about Brown, does I?

77
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:43,000
Actually, that's not quite true because I was, let me think about that, because I was involved with the NAACP Youth Council when I was in high school.

78
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:51,000
And they had, uh, a slogan, you know, Free by '63" (NAACP youth slogan) + Emancipation Proclamation centennial.

79
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:58,000
You know, the, Free by '63" (NAACP youth slogan) + Emancipation Proclamation centennial. So the, uh, I forgot, Jesus.

80
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:04,000
I had forgotten that I was involved with NAACP Youth Council.

81
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:09,000
Well, on that point, you kind of anticipated that, but it was going to be my next question, which is, were you, uh,

82
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:17,000
did you come from a race family and were you a young, were you an adolescent with much of that question from your mom?

83
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:25,000
No, particularly. It's, um...

84
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:30,000
There were, um...

85
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:37,000
episodes. I didn't think about them at the time, and they crystal, the significance of them crystallized later,

86
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:45,000
and they were going to visit my, you know, well, as I said, my, my, my uncle Gray, who was another role model of mine.

87
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:55,000
He had to leave Georgia because he, uh, he had a girlfriend who, our, our Alzheimer was being, you know, quite, quite striking.

88
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:04,000
And some white guy was pursuing her, and I don't know whether he killed him, but they had a confrontation. He at least beat the hell out of him.

89
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:12,000
And then he had to leave. He went to Detroit to live with his older brother, my uncle, in, in, in, in Detroit.

90
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:21,000
But later on, I mean, when I got to Harvard, as I mentioned in, in the, in the Malcolm X article, and was in this graduate,

91
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:27,000
it let me into this graduate seminar with C. Eric Lincoln, and, uh...

92
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:32,000
and, and with, and with, and with me young, and I had...

93
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:41,000
I started going to, uh, as I said, in the article, race was all around me, and I started, and, and, and, running to Malcolm X again.

94
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:52,000
And I started going to, what was then, Temple No. 11, which, which, Farrakhan, who was then known as, as Louis X.

95
00:13:52,000 --> 00:14:02,000
And listening, as I also say, in my notes to you, that I was very attracted to the, to Malcolm X's world view.

96
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:05,000
But I, um...

97
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:22,000
And so I started thinking about, going to Georgia, and you come out of, you come out of, the train station, and, and etched in stone, and, and the building, and, and the color, and white.

98
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:37,000
And also I, I had been, I had been in, in the chorus, as well. And I remember, and this is all, you said you'd interviewed, uh, the, the charades.

99
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:49,000
And the, I remember, being called into, they asked, for my next duty station, and they asked me, how would I like to go to Albany?

100
00:14:49,000 --> 00:15:04,000
And the only Albany, I knew it was Albany in New York. So I said, I thought to myself, oh, that's super. I can swoop down the Harlem, it, it, it, it, it, it, it, catcher, uh, and then I went down to, to Howard, because there was,

101
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:14,000
one of our rival fraternities, the capis had a, a big social event called the Capiton dance. So, and I had almost gone to Howard, um,

102
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:27,000
because I had been offered a super scholarship, and they had brought me down to Howard, and I walked across campus, and saw a million girls who looked like Hallibary.

103
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:42,000
And, um, I had a, a neighborhood friend, Carl McCall, who was, treasure, Lieutenant Governor of New York, at some point.

104
00:15:42,000 --> 00:16:02,000
And he had gone to Dartmouth, and he was there with, with, a, a guy, whose name will come to me, perhaps, who was a little older, whose mother was the principal of the famous, I think she was the, or he, or he had gone as an undergraduate to Dunbar High School, the famous black school in Washington.

105
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:14,000
And, and this guy was a basketball player, and he had, he had left Dartmouth, gone to Howard, and then we, and then we turned to, uh, to Dartmouth.

106
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:28,000
So, I was talking to my mother and friends about going to Howard, and then, and then going up to Cambridge, and they said in effect, uh, schmuck, take you behind the Cambridge.

107
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:51,000
So, the, uh, the, because back in those days, you were, there was a community, so it wasn't just you and your family, your church, you know, you know, about your exploits, and, uh, your, and your accomplishments.

108
00:16:51,000 --> 00:17:02,000
So, you had, in essence, you had the responsibility of the race, because we were told, we had to be twice as good as white people, white competitors.

109
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:20,000
So, you had that, that responsibility. But I must say that if you, if you grow up in, well, if you, if you remember the, the famous movie 10, or if you grew up in a, in a community where,

110
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:30,000
you, you believe that the, the women you encounter, or eight, nine, and ten, then you go to Howard and see, that they're really only fours and fives.

111
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:35,000
You know, uh, socially, you said, woof, have mercy Jesus.

112
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:44,000
So, with, I said, now you've gone, you've gone to Harvard, and Howard, Howard can wait, and so it didn't wait.

113
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:56,000
But then, depending on the other stories, just that when I looked at my, while I was at Howard and looked at my orders, I saw that it wasn't Albany, New York, but Albany, Georgia, or as the natives pronounced it all banny.

114
00:17:56,000 --> 00:18:13,000
And that was another, the Marine Corps was a very important formative experience, because most of the people, the military, I assume still, fundamentally a Southern institution, and the people that you had in the Corps were, especially the opera.

115
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:42,000
Especially the opera, at all, worse, um, with Southerners, and the enlisted men were Southerners, and, or young guys, whom the judge had told, we have two choices, the joint, or the Marine Corps, but it was, but I learned about, um, dimensions of white America that never would have learned otherwise, and I'd not been in the Corps.

116
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:44,000
When were you in America?

117
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:46,000
56, 59.

118
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:52,000
What were some of those, what were the examples of some of those things, you know?

119
00:18:52,000 --> 00:19:21,000
Well, the Marine Corps had, uh, a culture, and that you, they instilled in you, I don't know what they're doing now, because now all the uniforms look alike, and, uh, the whole period of, of training is not the same as it used to be.

120
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:38,000
But they, if you make a distinction between who you are or were as a civilian, and then as a, a jarhead, there are things that you do when you're a civilian that are civilized.

121
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:43,000
If it's raining or snowing, you go inside.

122
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:53,000
The, um, and what they teach you is when you think, that you cannot take another step, you can run five more miles.

123
00:19:53,000 --> 00:20:07,000
So you become acquainted with reserves, personal reserves that you would never otherwise have known, and that creates a certain, um, image, identity, which also can work against you.

124
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:13,000
Because people didn't think they're, you know, they're, uh, invulnerable.

125
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:29,000
Um, but it does, I mean, they, you develop a kind of superior already, attitude towards civilians, and to the army, and the Navy, the swabbies, because the army shoots from the 300-yard line, we shoot from the the 300-yard line.

126
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:39,000
So they instilled, they, for some of these guys, the core was their mother and their daddy.

127
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:51,000
I mean, I don't know, I don't know some of their personal stories, but for some of these guys, the Marine Corps was everything for them.

128
00:20:52,000 --> 00:21:01,000
And that, and trying to understand, um, where those needs came from, was educational.

129
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:19,000
And then they also, you become more, you become more humble, because I remember being in boot camp, and the, uh, in Parris Island + the Camp + then "Le Jeune", and then the camp, and then later on in Parris Island + the Camp + then "Le Jeune", that, um, I'm walking across.

130
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:26,000
The base and find myself humming the Everly Brothers.

131
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:44,000
That, and get indoctrinated in an, in an, in an atmosphere, because I had, you know, been going to story, building the stables, and, and was deep, and was deep into jazz, um, and our, and our, and our, and our, and our, and our, and B.

132
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:51,000
But, when you enveloped in an environment, it's, it's interesting how it can have, it can creep into your consciousness.

133
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:57,000
I'm walking around, the base humming, Everly Brothers.

134
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:13,000
And, and I'm still in touch with one of my old buddies, all of the way, when we weren't in the same outfit, just came up to visit me from, well, there was a big event in D.C. for the Buffalo Soldiers.

135
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:24,000
He's living in Savannah, where they just murdered, uh, outside of Jackson (Georgia), where they just murdered Troy, Troy Anthony Davis, and he wrote his bike up.

136
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:34,000
He was also, um, he came up, he must have sell his house and bought some, and then he, and then he wrote up, up here to Amherst, to, you know, to visit me.

137
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:39,000
So there is this, there is a fraternity at the States with you forever, actually.

138
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:48,000
So, coming up, Rincord, you went into, I went back to, I went back to Harvard.

139
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:51,000
Yeah, and you already enrolled there, briefly.

140
00:22:51,000 --> 00:23:07,000
Yeah, so, um, I'm interested to moving through the last half of the, of the 50s, things like, things like, huge things like, brown and muckum ray and, and a till and,

141
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:10,000
little rock and all.

142
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:18,000
I'm just wondering about how you're watching those things unfold and thinking about them at the time.

143
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:21,000
As you have best you can conjure your call?

144
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:30,000
I wasn't thinking much about the thing that I, that I think struck the consciousness of everyone.

145
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:40,000
And, subjectly, was the reason I've later discovered why many people of my generation joined SNCC, was the murder of Emmett Till,

146
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:45,000
because Jet had his picture displayed.

147
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:57,000
Um, and then at Harvard, I took an English course,

148
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:07,000
was a very famous literary, professor of literature at the time, Howard Mumford Jones.

149
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:12,000
And he had us reading Richard Wright, Uncle Tom's Children.

150
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:17,000
Uncle Tom's Children were below your mind.

151
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:24,000
And people still, I talked to my friends, colleagues in literature about the significance of that book,

152
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:34,000
because to me, I mean, I teach it in my, when I teach, um, civil rights on my Malcolm X Martin course,

153
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:37,000
I start the, the students off with Uncle Tom's Children.

154
00:24:37,000 --> 00:24:44,000
I want them to understand just how capricious racism, Southern racism was,

155
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:51,000
and how the least little thing could suddenly become a matter of life and death.

156
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:58,000
So I read Uncle Tom's Children, that helped, and then James Baldwin, Notes of a Native Son, he has an essay,

157
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:07,000
which in SNCC says, has ever been a Negro at some point is not consumed with rage and wants to.

158
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:13,000
And I said, oh, I'm not the only one.

159
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:26,000
So, and then it's, I was at Harvard, and that's when I, um, joined Northern Student Movement, Northern Student Movement was, as I mentioned,

160
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:31,000
was started by, um, when young whites undergraduate at, at, at Yale P.D.

161
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:39,000
a countryman, and it had city projects all around the country in Chicago and Detroit, and Boston, Hartford, New York.

162
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:44,000
Um, and they had somehow connected to NAD, because that's how I first met Stokely.

163
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:51,000
Um, I left out Chicago, Detroit, Hartford, and Hartford as well.

164
00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:58,000
And then when Peter decided to go back to school, they asked me to, they asked me to, to become executive director,

165
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:06,000
and I agreed to do that. So that took me, you know, going to visit the, you know, the city projects around the country.

166
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:18,000
Um, created opportunities like, to meet people like Jim and James and Grace Boggs.

167
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:21,000
Yeah, I have a range of questions about that.

168
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:29,000
Just, just, just went back, just a bit, and I'll ask you one more thing.

169
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:37,000
Um, just interested, um, is there anything more to say about, um, your mother?

170
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:47,000
Her, her, her influence was, was, um, incalculable.

171
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:52,000
Means she, in effect, devoted her life to me.

172
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:58,000
And that's another reason I tried to do, to do well to honor her, her commitment.

173
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:00,000
You don't make me cry.

174
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:02,000
It happens lots of reasons.

175
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:03,000
Yeah.

176
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:06,000
But she was a great, great person.

177
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:10,000
I had great relatives in my house.

178
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:12,000
uncles, and great relatives.

179
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:18,000
And that's what I, you see missing with this, this generation, there's no, there's no community.

180
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:21,000
You kind of belong to the community.

181
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:40,000
And, and where I lived on Walnut Avenue, the, it was still, you know, Jewish, Irish, um, Armenians.

182
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:47,000
The, um, in the, no, I went to Henry Lee Henry Lee Higginson School School.

183
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:50,000
That's, it was from Henry Lee Henry Lee Higginson School School that I went to Latin school.

184
00:27:50,000 --> 00:28:03,000
So you had all of these different nationalities in your, in your classroom, but the black community in your neighborhood, um, mostly you up, went to the same church.

185
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:09,000
But you were, you were, you belonged to everybody.

186
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:21,000
And you recognized, but for example, when a few years ago, Grace Boggs was telling me about Detroit and she was saying, Billy, we can't go out and organize the way we used to.

187
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:29,000
Because you got these gang bangers, you, you're taking your life in the hands just walking out in the street.

188
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:45,000
So the changes, the changes, uh, I mean, truthfully, the races in limbo as has never been before.

189
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:50,000
And, um, there's a confusion.

190
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:55,000
The young generation is, is a historical.

191
00:28:55,000 --> 00:29:00,000
It's not, not their fault, but you don't have what we had.

192
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:08,000
I mean, we don't have black newspapers.

193
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:10,000
We don't have black radio stations.

194
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:12,000
Five corporations control the media.

195
00:29:13,000 --> 00:29:28,000
So that there is a different, I don't blame the young people because you didn't, in our previous history, you didn't have to teach people what it meant to be black.

196
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:37,000
Um, there was continuity, but now we are, because most of black, most of our history, we have been a southern people.

197
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:41,000
But now we are two and three generations, we move from the south.

198
00:29:41,000 --> 00:29:50,000
And now you have all this confusion about gender or identity and sexual orientation identity, where women, black women,

199
00:29:50,000 --> 00:29:58,000
who identify as female gender before they do, and gay, who identify as gay before, before black.

200
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:01,000
And now you have the senses with all these different definitions.

201
00:30:01,000 --> 00:30:04,000
Are you Hispanic, white, and Hispanic?

202
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:09,000
And now we have new, quote, black people here.

203
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:19,000
You have black people from Africa and from the West Indies, who don't have America's history behind them.

204
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:31,000
So, you know, I remember, you know, being in Harlem, being passed by black car drivers, well, been a typically black.

205
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:47,000
Or you, or getting off the, uh, flying to D.C., and you have African, Indian, Bengals that may or may not pick you up,

206
00:30:47,000 --> 00:30:52,000
because they want to take white people to the Virginia, to the suburbs.

207
00:30:52,000 --> 00:31:00,000
So, there's a great confusion about race in America today, which of course the evil people take advantage of, divide it.

208
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:04,000
What, what, they used to divide you by color.

209
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:08,000
Now they divide you by gender and whatever.

210
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:11,000
Which was the church in Oxford?

211
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:13,000
My church, Charles Street AME Church (Boston).

212
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:15,000
Charles Street AME Church (Boston).

213
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:18,000
Charles Street AME Church (Boston).

214
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:36,000
Did you, did you remember your early, don't you still feel that close time at church?

215
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:39,000
Are you spiritual or social life?

216
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:47,000
Not particularly, except in the service you, you become religious when you're being shot at.

217
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:53,000
No, I've never been.

218
00:31:53,000 --> 00:32:05,000
I mean, I enjoy the church experience, but like I approach to, actually, I mean, a good, a good black preacher will just, you know,

219
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:10,000
at least start rapping, or she, but now I've heard some very good female preachers.

220
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:17,000
It's a whole different, a milieu, it's a whole different experience.

221
00:32:17,000 --> 00:32:32,000
A good preacher will, you know, will, I will respond independently of whether I believe in the theology, but I'll certainly respond to a good preacher.

222
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:42,000
I'm going to mention to the, that one of the things that you felt in those years, I'm thinking now, like, 60s, you're moving back into Harvard,

223
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:55,000
but you felt, quite understandably, felt the curriculum of radiation, was an assembly of principal sort of institutional mechanism for acting on that.

224
00:32:55,000 --> 00:33:03,000
Yeah, I think I think I, I think I did keep in touch with the NAACP, but I was in, in Cambridge, so I went back to Boston,

225
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:07,000
wasn't like being in Boston in high school.

226
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:23,000
I think in it's them, because you saw the situation of black people in different regions of the country, and so that was educational.

227
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:31,000
And while I was, our office was in, was adjacent to Harlem, not quite in Harlem.

228
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:43,000
On the down, and I worked with another great guy whose story needs to be told, Jesse Gray, the Harlem went straight to the leader.

229
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:53,000
And that was another question, and that introduced me to the whole question of the history of black communist.

230
00:33:53,000 --> 00:34:07,000
And I, and the, how they had been, how they, when they insisted that, that raised Trump class, how that was a non-starter for the party.

231
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:13,000
And Jesse had been, was another Josh, had been in the merchant Marines.

232
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:23,000
So I got, I got that history of struggle from, you know, black, of, of, of black leftists.

233
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:36,000
And, and then Jesse taught me something about organizing, because he had an office like in East Harlem, East London, 14th East London.

234
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:53,000
And then, when people wanted to, got fed up with, being exploited by the landlords, he, and he was, you know, was known, written up in the papers.

235
00:34:53,000 --> 00:34:59,000
They were called the office, and then we would go over to the, to the apartments.

236
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:15,000
And he would give them, you know, tap, tell them what they had to do, but you had to keep collecting the rent money and put it in the bank or somewhere so that when the strike was over, when they came to kick you out, you could have paid, paid the background.

237
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:28,000
But it was a very important lesson about how to organize, that the secret of organizing is, is, is convincing people to organize themselves, although they may not realize that it's what's happening at the time.

238
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:36,000
They're ready, and then you give them what needs to be done so that they organize, they organize, actually organize themselves.

239
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:46,000
So that was a very important lesson. And Jesse was, Jesse was a great spirit.

240
00:35:46,000 --> 00:36:02,000
Oh, God. I guess he must, well, everybody seemed to hold back when he, I guess he was probably, because he died young.

241
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:05,000
I guess he was somewhere between 40 and 50.

242
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:22,000
And he was, if he was, much of a range, and then World War II and those 60, he was 24.

243
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:25,000
Yeah, probably mid 40s, probably mid 40s.

244
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:51,000
I wanted to ask, and this is maybe, maybe the connection, I wanted to ask, one of the very ancient things about Northern Student Movement, as you've noted in things you've written, is that after that, some early, after it's say, on touring black youths and communities, there was a more structural shift in the thinking and the critique and organizing became, can you organize and become a big focus, obviously.

245
00:36:51,000 --> 00:37:05,000
And under your tenure as a director and predates, I think it's important to know, SNCC's later community work in some ways, is that your sense?

246
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:20,000
No, because SNCC influenced us. I don't, it would be difficult to draw the line of demarcation. People may have been doing community organizing.

247
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:35,000
Even under, even under Peter. But it became, after everybody began to understand the problem was much greater than, to doing kids.

248
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:48,000
SNCC was a major influence on our thinking. And then we had, in Detroit, we had,

249
00:37:48,000 --> 00:38:07,000
the union folk, and we had the guys from Detroit who were organizing, and although they weren't in Northern Student Movement, per se, we were in touch with them.

250
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:17,000
So they were, they were a role model. And there was a great guy whose, whose history needs to be told, named Kenny Cockrel.

251
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:29,000
And Kenny was one of the organizers with a guy named General Baker of Black Youth in Detroit and became a lawyer.

252
00:38:29,000 --> 00:38:39,000
And he was, the only person I have met, who almost could rap like Malcolm X. He was a fantastic rapper.

253
00:38:39,000 --> 00:38:56,000
We became a lawyer and he had a few wonderful cases. He had a case with this black police woman who got into some altercation with a white officer in the police station garage.

254
00:38:56,000 --> 00:39:07,000
And he got her off. And then there was another, another case of a black worker on the line who also had another off.

255
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:20,000
He may even have killed the coworker. And Kenny got him off as well. And then he ran the office. He was elected to the Detroit City Council.

256
00:39:20,000 --> 00:39:35,000
And decided that that was duplicitous to try and convince people that that City Council could make the changes that were necessary.

257
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:46,000
So he resigned from the City Council. And then unfortunately he had a heart attack. And he died in his early 50s.

258
00:39:46,000 --> 00:39:52,000
But he was, as we used to say, he was a bad motorcycle.

259
00:39:52,000 --> 00:40:03,000
In a economic shift to New York in 1963 and across 64, you're obviously, as you mentioned, traveling to C and S and working.

260
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:08,000
The City's words involved. And you'll go to Mississippi as well in 64.

261
00:40:08,000 --> 00:40:19,000
But I want to ask about how this relocation to New York brought you back in contact with Malcolm X and how the arguments you were hearing him present.

262
00:40:19,000 --> 00:40:28,000
How you took them up and considered them in a relationship to what you were observing and through Northern Student Movement, through SNCC, through.

263
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:43,000
Well, as I mentioned in that critique, I'm in high school and we're watching Martin and Martin is saying things like, if any of the others to be spilled, let it be ours.

264
00:40:43,000 --> 00:40:48,000
And we're saying, oh no, no, we said something a lot stronger than that actually.

265
00:40:48,000 --> 00:41:02,000
No, no, we were not, we were not persuaded by that. But when I got to into New York, as I also say in the article Malcolm X was everywhere.

266
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:10,000
He was always having these rallies on 125th Street, so was Michaux. There were these guys, Eddie, Pork, Job, Davis.

267
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:21,000
They brought their ladders or whatever and they would be wrapping in front of the hotel Theresa. And Malcolm X would be walking.

268
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:34,000
And then I would go down to the restaurant. And as I said, I also had brought him after we had reconnected at Harvard, I brought him up to Harvard a couple of times a week.

269
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:48,000
I also mentioned, I don't know why I assumed him because he knew Leslie, but he did, he even visited me at my house when I, before I left Boston.

270
00:41:48,000 --> 00:42:00,000
But he never tried to convert me. He never tried to convert me. Because I wasn't about to give up spare ribs and chasing young girls.

271
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:05,000
So I couldn't join the nation. I don't know.

272
00:42:05,000 --> 00:42:15,000
Tell me about how you began to figure out through the political critique that Malcolm X's advancing.

273
00:42:15,000 --> 00:42:26,000
Well, people don't appreciate, as I also wrote, yeah. Malcolm X, Malcolm X, as I wrote in the piece in the same way that Marx is the fundamental critic of capitalism.

274
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:36,000
And in the end, the fundamental critic of colonialism. To my mind, Malcolm X is the fundamental critic of American racism.

275
00:42:36,000 --> 00:42:47,000
And he would be critiquing. And what people also don't appreciate is Malcolm X was as hard on black people as he was on white people.

276
00:42:47,000 --> 00:43:02,000
And he would talk about, you know, you don't want to, you talk about your outnumbered, at the man since you were a career, if I 900 million Chinese, you don't say your outnumbered there.

277
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:17,000
He got you thinking about how you'd been brainwashed. And then he would say when he was critiquing Martin, he would talk about the sit-ins. And he would say, well, who sits?

278
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:29,000
You know, cripples sit. Old lady, he didn't say cripples. That's it. But disabled people sit. The old women sit. Baby sit. We don't need to sit. We need to stand up.

279
00:43:29,000 --> 00:43:52,000
He had a way, as I said, also said, in a village voice piece, if you want to know what was going on in world events, or national events, all you did was walk on down to 125th Street, to tune in on the X, because he was a prodigious reader.

280
00:43:52,000 --> 00:44:18,000
I think I made an automation and make it plain. But I caught him once reading William F. Buckley's William F. Buckley's National Review. And I asked, that's why Saturday Review was Norman Cousins + (his daughter) Andrea Cousins, Norman Cousins, and Norman Cousins + (his daughter) Andrea Cousins worked with Northern Student Movement. In fact, she works right down. She's a lay therapist down in Northampton.

281
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:27,000
But I asked why was he really William F. Buckley's National Review? And he said, because you never can tell where you come across a good idea.

282
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:41,000
He had a prodigious work habits and read every several papers a day, magazines, and always reading.

283
00:44:41,000 --> 00:44:57,000
And I mean to answer your question, I was agreed with his critique of the movement and the duplicity of the government.

284
00:44:57,000 --> 00:45:09,000
I mean, we have him in eyes on the prize, because the first rebellion in this country is in Birmingham in May of 1963, when there's an attempt to whack Martin.

285
00:45:09,000 --> 00:45:21,000
They blow up, they bombed the A.G. Gaston Motel. They also bombed A.D. King, his brother's house. And it was then that the masses, the black masses of Birmingham erupted.

286
00:45:21,000 --> 00:45:29,000
And Malcolm X makes this point that when Bull Connor was using fire hoses and whatever Kennedy said he couldn't intervene.

287
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:39,000
But as soon as the black people erupted, they nationalized the guard. And Malcolm X had, we have a famous scene. Well, it's famous to me.

288
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:51,000
In the eyes episode, The Time Has Come (1964-66)" where Malcolm X says, and there was no new law.

289
00:45:51,000 --> 00:46:03,000
So, and then that's the snickering. You have the March on Washington, the Mad Girl ever since it just been assassinated.

290
00:46:03,000 --> 00:46:09,000
And the snick workers in Georgia had been arrested.

291
00:46:09,000 --> 00:46:31,000
For picketing outside the business of our recall of a juror, they invoke some 19th century law to arrest the snickers. And the FBI just stands around and takes notes but does nothing.

292
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:43,000
And then 64 after (Michael "Mickey") Schwerner, (James) Chaney, (Andrew) Goodman, they kill J. Edgar Hoover says that they can't protect civil rights workers.

293
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:49,000
They could COINTELPRO but they couldn't protect us.

294
00:46:49,000 --> 00:47:03,000
And that's where with worse statement comes down a little later down the road. I mean black power doesn't drop from the sky.

295
00:47:03,000 --> 00:47:25,000
And so, it was jail, a zillion damn times. People get tired. As Mrs. (Fannie Lou) Hamer's says, people get tired of being sick and tired. And relying on a government that does nothing for you and collaborates with the southern races when we were confronting.

296
00:47:25,000 --> 00:47:37,000
Yeah. Let me ask you a bill to talk a little bit. Let's just spend a little bit of time talking. You teach it obviously and have taught it.

297
00:47:37,000 --> 00:47:51,000
In depth, I've thought so much about this. Let's talk a little bit more about Malcolm X's critique of race in this role and function in this society.

298
00:47:51,000 --> 00:48:11,000
Well, one of the things Malcolm X used to say is that history was the most rewarding of all subjects to study. And I remember being in the mosque and he was quoting from a book called Antislavery: The Crusade for Freedom in America by Dwight Lowell Dumond which is of course now out of print.

299
00:48:11,000 --> 00:48:31,000
And Malcolm X was talking about the slave power. See, the history is all about how do you contextualize it?

300
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:43,000
What would you think? Well, suppose you were E.T. coming down from space and you were trying to understand. You read about the glories of America.

301
00:48:43,000 --> 00:49:03,000
And then someone was asking about the greatest presidents and invariably in that lineup is Abraham Lincoln. So then ET asked me what president was here. And you say, if you've done your homework, he was the 16th president.

302
00:49:03,000 --> 00:49:29,000
Now, what is your image of America if you are taught that of the 15 presidents before a tenuous slave owners? How does that square with the image of democracy? Or again, in relationship to the government's treaties with the Indians?

303
00:49:29,000 --> 00:49:49,000
And once, well, we understand that they broke the treaties. But how many treaties did they break? They broke all 400. So where is the morality in which the society garrips itself?

304
00:49:49,000 --> 00:50:07,000
And that's what Malcolm X would do. Malcolm X would just throw the history at you and make you rethink what you had been taught.

305
00:50:07,000 --> 00:50:36,000
On one level, all societies like to think well of themselves. That's not unusual in itself. In fact, it's dirty. It's dirty, girl. But America is very pompous about it. And we've just seen it with Troy Anthony Davis. The whole world, the whole world, embassies all around the world.

306
00:50:36,000 --> 00:51:02,000
There were protests. And I asked my students try to get them to understand how they're being brainwashed. I said, did you watch the Arab Spring? They said, you watch what's happening in Tunisia? Yes. You watch what's happening in Egypt? Yes. So let me ask you something. It's not only to establish the fact that the American media can bring you on-site coverage from the Middle East.

307
00:51:02,000 --> 00:51:15,000
When's the last time you saw on-site coverage from Iraq or Afghanistan? And the answer is, or from the West Bank or Gaza or Tel Aviv. The answer is never. Never.

308
00:51:15,000 --> 00:51:33,000
So you're being... I asked them also if they have a language to read for our newspapers just to see what stories are covered and how they're covered abroad and what stories are covered and not covered. And how they're covered here in America.

309
00:51:33,000 --> 00:51:57,000
Because Americans are the most deceived, except for the people who want to be deceived. But it's... It's easier to maintain control over people if you take away their critical thinking.

310
00:51:57,000 --> 00:52:17,000
And unfortunately, that seems to be... Mental retardation seems to be sweeping the country. And I just wrote a quick piece of my friends were calling me after they had been following these Republican debates and they call and said, what is happening in America?

311
00:52:17,000 --> 00:52:32,000
How can these people be potential presidents of your country? The outside world doesn't understand what's going on. But America has lost its credibility in the world.

312
00:52:32,000 --> 00:52:50,000
Well, it had lost it before under Bush. There was no place in the world. Bush could go whether or not protest against him. Also not covered by the media. When he went during his first term, when he went to London, he couldn't ride and he had to take a helicopter to Windsor Palace.

313
00:52:50,000 --> 00:53:11,000
And the Lord Mayor, there were 15,000 security in a cost every citizen of London, two pounds to pay for his security. And the Lord Mayor said Bush was the most unwelcome visitor since William of Orange. And they would have preferred to give five pounds and have him not come, then spend two pounds for his security when he did come.

314
00:53:11,000 --> 00:53:32,000
But none of this is unpleasantness is shared with the American people. So we live in a media cocoon which is improved increasingly disastrous.

315
00:53:32,000 --> 00:54:01,000
I'm sure we'll come back to the media question when we talk about the effort to develop black studies curriculum. But let me ask you, holding that point, for now we ask you about your experience trying to help with an effort fundamentally to restructure the politics of Mississippi and through that effort.

316
00:54:01,000 --> 00:54:08,000
National politics of race around the MVP because you would go down to Mississippi in 64.

317
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:35,000
Well, this is, you know, the government was trying to derail the student protests. And there were two opinions in Singapore. A lot of people were committed to sit-ins and protest.

318
00:54:35,000 --> 00:55:04,000
But the government talked about the power of the vote. And so Robert Parris Moses goes down to Mississippi. And they had organized the freedom because the Mississippi politicians had claimed black people were happy and content and were interested in voting.

319
00:55:04,000 --> 00:55:28,000
So they organized the freedom vote in 63,000 people voted. And that was also to acquaint them as later stocally and didn't lounge county to acquaint them with the procedures. The, in out of those procedures, they decided to form a political party and to challenge three of the white, the white congressman.

320
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:54,000
So they nominated Mrs. (Fannie Lou) Hamer's and Victoria Gray Adams and Annie Devine. And the lawyers went and gathered evidence as the extensive nature of voter suppression in Mississippi. And then that was a little counter-tomped for the movement because SNCC was working in the America.

321
00:55:54,000 --> 00:56:14,000
The people working with the National Lawyers Guild and that, and they were two leftists for, of course, they got red-bated, two leftists for Allard Lowenstein and NAACP. But I worked all the time with William Kunstler and Arthur Kinoy.

322
00:56:14,000 --> 00:56:43,000
So when I came back to organize, to help organize the congressional support for the challenge. And the guy who was really most instrumental who was also not gotten recognition that he had.

323
00:56:44,000 --> 00:57:06,000
And he deserved was William Fitts Ryan. When the Congress can reconvene in January, it is he who put forward the resolution because Congress makes its own laws. And therefore the three white congressmen had to step aside while the resolution was being debated.

324
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:26,000
And when he raised it, then 50 or 60 other congressmen rose up to support him. And then when the vote was eventually taken, the MFDP got, if I remember correctly, 149 votes, which was not enough because you had to have a majority of the 435.

325
00:57:26,000 --> 00:57:39,000
But at least temporarily, we had demonstrated just how crooked the system is.

326
00:57:39,000 --> 00:57:48,000
Coming out of Atlantic City and then the January Chan-Fail January Challenge.

327
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:59,000
Did that, at that point, with those experiences of altered your basic perspective or just confirmed it?

328
00:57:59,000 --> 00:58:17,000
I'm trying to, I wasn't in Atlantic City. I was somewhere else, but some, was I back in Mississippi? I wasn't in Atlantic City. No, because they had come up in the buses. You better turn this on. I think it was chasing.

329
00:58:17,000 --> 00:58:37,000
We're back after a short break, just to get a drink for a moment. I was going to ask your perspective on that. Questions before we stopped. Did the MFDP experiences alter, adjust, or large-life confirm your perspective at the time?

330
00:58:37,000 --> 00:58:55,000
I was thinking about that. My strongest memory, not memory. The strongest impact the MFDP did for me was not quite about politics per se.

331
00:58:55,000 --> 00:59:15,000
I was sitting in Mrs. (Fannie Lou) Hamer's, and understanding that all of my education, that there were people like Mrs. (Fannie Lou) Hamer's who could see the world with a clarity that was infinitely superior to mine.

332
00:59:15,000 --> 00:59:35,000
They had a wholesomeness. Is she going to make me cry again? If you weren't in touch with it, you just didn't realize that it existed.

333
00:59:35,000 --> 00:59:49,000
It was different. Malcolm X was somebody that you could, there were two people in the far anywhere. Malcolm X was one of the other. My second mother, Katherine Dunham.

334
00:59:49,000 --> 01:00:12,000
But it humbled you to realize that all of this book learning and whatever was secondary to a particular kind of acuity about what makes the world go around and what is important in the world, what's important in life.

335
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:41,000
So I think that's the strongest impact getting to know people. I mean, Robert Parris Moses was in Mississippi, prior I got there with Amzie Moore, and they tell me that he was taking people down the register and he got beaten up severely and went back and took off his t-shirt and washed it.

336
01:00:42,000 --> 01:00:54,000
And then put it back on and went back down to the courthouse. But he said he was washing the shirt because he didn't want the blood to scare the people.

337
01:00:54,000 --> 01:01:11,000
I mean, there is a heroism that defies description. So those are the things that, because Mrs. Wies just called Mississippi the state when he was going in.

338
01:01:11,000 --> 01:01:30,000
And that's actually one of the reasons that I went ahead and got married because if I wanted something out of life in case I got killed, I wanted to partake of life.

339
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:45,000
I mean, she was a cool woman. She was super cool, but I had to spend a vast enough time. I just was trying. It was kind of like preparing your will.

340
01:01:45,000 --> 01:01:55,000
What did you do? 60. I think it was 65.

341
01:01:55,000 --> 01:01:59,000
Is something new from the Mississippi contest? No, no, no.

342
01:01:59,000 --> 01:02:05,000
But you had that experience back then.

343
01:02:05,000 --> 01:02:12,000
I went back to the state for a while.

344
01:02:12,000 --> 01:02:14,000
I'm sorry, you went back after the...

345
01:02:14,000 --> 01:02:30,000
Now after January, I went back for a while. No, I married this very attractive young woman who I met in New York. Turn it off.

346
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:37,000
February 21, 1965.

347
01:02:37,000 --> 01:02:40,000
We were in an...

348
01:02:40,000 --> 01:02:56,000
Innocent was having a meeting upstate New York and all of our project directors and people were there when we heard that Malcolm X had been killed.

349
01:02:56,000 --> 01:03:05,000
First was unbelievable. Then you get pissed out of your mind.

350
01:03:05,000 --> 01:03:16,000
But he was in it. Every once in a while, history will produce someone. And this village's voice piece I wrote on the 20th anniversary of Malcolm X's assassination.

351
01:03:16,000 --> 01:03:29,000
I was saying, Martin kind of embodied the personality of the south. But Malcolm X embodied the personality of the urban north, black person.

352
01:03:29,000 --> 01:03:36,000
So they didn't just kill a man, they killed the prototype.

353
01:03:36,000 --> 01:03:47,000
So we came on back to the city to find out what had happened and whatever.

354
01:03:47,000 --> 01:03:59,000
And then that day, well later for the funeral, I was just thinking,

355
01:03:59,000 --> 01:04:07,000
now suppose where Wilkins had died, these liens of people, you know, be trying to go to his funeral.

356
01:04:07,000 --> 01:04:19,000
I don't have anything against where Wilkins was just a different kind of image.

357
01:04:19,000 --> 01:04:31,000
So that was an irreplaceable loss.

358
01:04:31,000 --> 01:04:41,000
What were your choices in front of you at that point with Northern Student Movement and the Graduate School and all?

359
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:47,000
And how did you move forward from early 1965?

360
01:04:47,000 --> 01:04:57,000
I was just thinking about that. I got married, went back to school.

361
01:04:57,000 --> 01:05:12,000
I was still doing, running back in Washington, New York. I had a job at Columbia for a while with the Gismos father.

362
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:18,000
I'm trying to think of it. Oh, we did. That's what Vincent Harding called me again.

363
01:05:18,000 --> 01:05:25,000
We put together this TV program called Black Heritage: A History of Afro-Americans, which is on CBS.

364
01:05:25,000 --> 01:05:34,000
And many of the people whom he had, Vincent Harding and John Henrik Clarke.

365
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:43,000
In essence, it was the first representation of black studies, certainly on television.

366
01:05:43,000 --> 01:05:50,000
But CBS would put it on five o'clock in the morning, TV in those days would go off at one or whatever.

367
01:05:50,000 --> 01:05:55,000
They would come back with, I forgot what they used to call us to come back on at five or six.

368
01:05:55,000 --> 01:06:02,000
And then the very first thing I would be Black Heritage: A History of Afro-Americans. And then years later, some students were trying to track it down.

369
01:06:02,000 --> 01:06:07,000
And I don't remember whether it was CBS or whether it was later HBO.

370
01:06:07,000 --> 01:06:20,000
Because HBO did the trial of James Earl Ray and then denied that they had done it.

371
01:06:20,000 --> 01:06:27,000
And as I said, most of the people with the bogs and the law and the people who were involved in that Black Heritage: A History of Afro-Americans series,

372
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:40,000
Vincent Harding invited to Atlanta after Martin was assassinated. And Coretta asked him to become director of the Martin Luther King Jr. Center for Nonviolent Social Change.

373
01:06:40,000 --> 01:06:47,000
I think I had a mistaken sense of when Black Heritage: A History of Afro-Americans aired.

374
01:06:47,000 --> 01:06:50,000
It began airing...

375
01:06:50,000 --> 01:06:52,000
I have...

376
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:54,000
Proximity?

377
01:06:54,000 --> 01:06:57,000
Somewhere between...

378
01:06:57,000 --> 01:06:59,000
I think 65 or 66, maybe 67.

379
01:06:59,000 --> 01:07:01,000
Okay, I was thinking 67.

380
01:07:01,000 --> 01:07:04,000
Yeah, somewhere. Am I even in 68?

381
01:07:04,000 --> 01:07:05,000
Okay.

382
01:07:05,000 --> 01:07:09,000
Somewhere in that, I think, in that three-year period.

383
01:07:09,000 --> 01:07:12,000
Well, are there...

384
01:07:12,000 --> 01:07:14,000
I'm sure there are many, but other...

385
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:17,000
Especially some things that you won't say about the...

386
01:07:17,000 --> 01:07:22,000
The shift of context now back to graduate school and...

387
01:07:22,000 --> 01:07:31,000
You know, finding your academic life now engaging these same questions, but from that angle.

388
01:07:31,000 --> 01:07:38,000
Well, I had discovered another hero to study.

389
01:07:38,000 --> 01:07:41,000
Frantz Fanon.

390
01:07:41,000 --> 01:07:42,000
So I was...

391
01:07:42,000 --> 01:07:45,000
And I gave that to you, the Algerian War of Independence (1954-62).

392
01:07:45,000 --> 01:07:48,000
The...

393
01:07:48,000 --> 01:07:53,000
So...

394
01:07:53,000 --> 01:07:56,000
Plunging myself into the...

395
01:07:56,000 --> 01:07:59,000
Into the Algerian War of Independence (1954-62).

396
01:07:59,000 --> 01:08:01,000
The...

397
01:08:01,000 --> 01:08:04,000
And appreciating...

398
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:06,000
Frantz Fanon.

399
01:08:06,000 --> 01:08:08,000
So...

400
01:08:08,000 --> 01:08:10,000
Did you discover that another hero?

401
01:08:10,000 --> 01:08:12,000
Was that Frantz Fanon?

402
01:08:12,000 --> 01:08:15,000
I mean, he came across...

403
01:08:15,000 --> 01:08:18,000
No, well...

404
01:08:18,000 --> 01:08:21,000
Frantz Fanon emerged in the movement.

405
01:08:21,000 --> 01:08:29,000
Because many people who were opposed to Martin's nonviolence would quote Frantz Fanon.

406
01:08:29,000 --> 01:08:34,000
Because Frantz Fanon talked about veranda colonialism" and the veranda colonialism".

407
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:37,000
So, never read like it.

408
01:08:37,000 --> 01:08:39,000
They don't need that.

409
01:08:39,000 --> 01:08:41,000
Never read about it.

410
01:08:41,000 --> 01:08:44,000
And then they were squat about the Algerian War of Independence (1954-62).

411
01:08:44,000 --> 01:08:56,000
But they would just take an exit from Frantz Fanon and use it to contravene Martin's notion of nonviolence.

412
01:08:56,000 --> 01:08:59,000
So, then I decided to read the book.

413
01:08:59,000 --> 01:09:05,000
And then from there I decided, you know, I went on to try and understand the whole...

414
01:09:05,000 --> 01:09:06,000
You know, the whole...

415
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:08,000
Because then every other thing...

416
01:09:08,000 --> 01:09:10,000
All kinds of other things open up.

417
01:09:10,000 --> 01:09:12,000
You know, the...

418
01:09:12,000 --> 01:09:16,000
You know, the contribution, the French Africans in World War II.

419
01:09:16,000 --> 01:09:23,000
In the liberation of Paris, the Allies insisted that the Black troops not march.

420
01:09:23,000 --> 01:09:33,000
They went and got anybody who did look black, Egyptians, whatever other Europeans to march, you know, down the Shaman's

421
01:09:33,000 --> 01:09:36,000
allies and the Austro-Tremor.

422
01:09:36,000 --> 01:09:40,000
I mean, the racism is incredible.

423
01:09:40,000 --> 01:09:43,000
And...

424
01:09:43,000 --> 01:09:47,000
So, that just opened up a whole different...

425
01:09:47,000 --> 01:09:56,000
Broadened my perspective about what Malcolm X was talking about, how rewarding a subject of study history is.

426
01:09:56,000 --> 01:09:58,000
But you begin to put things together.

427
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:00,000
Because for history is...

428
01:10:00,000 --> 01:10:02,000
I tell my students, history is just...

429
01:10:02,000 --> 01:10:04,000
It's not about dates.

430
01:10:04,000 --> 01:10:11,000
You understand the significance of dates and events when you understand the continuity.

431
01:10:11,000 --> 01:10:13,000
How things are connected.

432
01:10:13,000 --> 01:10:15,000
You remember, it's not to...

433
01:10:15,000 --> 01:10:19,000
But just to remember dates abstractly, doesn't mean anything to you.

434
01:10:19,000 --> 01:10:21,000
What is the flow of history?

435
01:10:21,000 --> 01:10:25,000
How do we get from A to B to C to D?

436
01:10:25,000 --> 01:10:31,000
And once you begin to understand the flow, then things become remarkably clearer.

437
01:10:31,000 --> 01:10:32,000
And even...

438
01:10:32,000 --> 01:10:34,000
You may even remember them.

439
01:10:34,000 --> 01:10:36,000
I have to...

440
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:38,000
I have to...

441
01:10:38,000 --> 01:10:42,000
The graduate faculty at Harvard responded to the work you were doing at the University of Medicine.

442
01:10:42,000 --> 01:10:44,000
Well, I was...

443
01:10:44,000 --> 01:10:48,000
A study with Erik H. Erikson.

444
01:10:48,000 --> 01:10:51,000
And initially, I was going to be a shrink.

445
01:10:51,000 --> 01:10:56,000
Because I loved Freud.

446
01:10:56,000 --> 01:10:59,000
And...

447
01:10:59,000 --> 01:11:03,000
And they had told me...

448
01:11:03,000 --> 01:11:07,000
What was this class I was taking with?

449
01:11:07,000 --> 01:11:09,000
Edwin G. Boring?

450
01:11:09,000 --> 01:11:11,000
Edward Edwin G. Boring?

451
01:11:11,000 --> 01:11:15,000
He was a psychologist.

452
01:11:15,000 --> 01:11:17,000
Interesting guy.

453
01:11:17,000 --> 01:11:20,000
But the...

454
01:11:22,000 --> 01:11:26,000
We went to...

455
01:11:28,000 --> 01:11:32,000
A mental hospital in Waltham.

456
01:11:33,000 --> 01:11:37,000
And there was a black guy there.

457
01:11:37,000 --> 01:11:44,000
And at the time, we were studying this English guy, non-directive therapy.

458
01:11:44,000 --> 01:11:49,000
So when you're involved with a relationship with...

459
01:11:49,000 --> 01:11:52,000
In that diatic relationship, the two of you...

460
01:11:52,000 --> 01:11:55,000
You're never supposed to impose yourself.

461
01:11:55,000 --> 01:11:59,000
And so, you know, the typical technique is...

462
01:11:59,000 --> 01:12:02,000
When they say something, you simply repeat it.

463
01:12:02,000 --> 01:12:04,000
So he asked me,

464
01:12:04,000 --> 01:12:06,000
Are you one, two?

465
01:12:06,000 --> 01:12:08,000
And I said, Am I one?

466
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:11,000
And it turned out he was a World War I vet.

467
01:12:11,000 --> 01:12:16,000
And racism had driven him crazy.

468
01:12:16,000 --> 01:12:19,000
And then the field changed.

469
01:12:19,000 --> 01:12:26,000
The field went from psychoanalysis to drug therapy.

470
01:12:27,000 --> 01:12:31,000
And then when I discovered phenol, I said, Well, that's the psychology.

471
01:12:31,000 --> 01:12:34,000
I'm interested in it.

472
01:12:34,000 --> 01:12:36,000
That liberation cycle.

473
01:12:36,000 --> 01:12:37,000
Yeah, liberation therapy.

474
01:12:37,000 --> 01:12:39,000
That's what I'm interested in.

475
01:12:39,000 --> 01:12:44,000
So I made this switch from Freud to phenol.

476
01:12:44,000 --> 01:12:46,000
In fact, years ago,

477
01:12:46,000 --> 01:12:52,000
I brought a man of phenol here to speak before she died.

478
01:12:52,000 --> 01:12:55,000
Actually, he's alleged to a committed suicide,

479
01:12:55,000 --> 01:12:57,000
which I don't understand.

480
01:12:57,000 --> 01:12:59,000
Josie Fanon.

481
01:12:59,000 --> 01:13:01,000
Have you ever been to...

482
01:13:01,000 --> 01:13:03,000
Algiers?

483
01:13:03,000 --> 01:13:06,000
Paris?

484
01:13:06,000 --> 01:13:09,000
J'aime Paris.

485
01:13:14,000 --> 01:13:17,000
Let's talk about the merchants after...

486
01:13:17,000 --> 01:13:20,000
Well, actually, maybe stop and...

487
01:13:20,000 --> 01:13:23,000
Ask you about...

488
01:13:23,000 --> 01:13:36,000
The events of spring of 1968 and how they were in their course in a year or so lead to the notion of the anti-government.

489
01:13:36,000 --> 01:13:42,000
I may be, it may be a good point to talk about time.

490
01:13:42,000 --> 01:13:45,000
And then how do you along view of Dr. King.

491
01:13:45,000 --> 01:13:48,000
Well, as I said, my initial view of mind.

492
01:13:48,000 --> 01:13:51,000
I met Martin a couple of times in the course of the movement.

493
01:13:51,000 --> 01:13:54,000
But he didn't make any particular...

494
01:13:54,000 --> 01:13:57,000
And of course, I had been in Selma when he turned us around.

495
01:13:57,000 --> 01:14:02,000
Yeah, I was in Selma for the third march, because there were three.

496
01:14:02,000 --> 01:14:05,000
And in fact, SCLC...

497
01:14:05,000 --> 01:14:10,000
You know, the original march was supposed to be for...

498
01:14:10,000 --> 01:14:13,000
to carry Jimmie Lee Jackson's body to the Capitol.

499
01:14:13,000 --> 01:14:17,000
But SCLC toned it down.

500
01:14:17,000 --> 01:14:20,000
And made it a voting rights march.

501
01:14:20,000 --> 01:14:25,000
And so they called for us, and I came down with the innocent people.

502
01:14:25,000 --> 01:14:31,000
But in fact, you would not be able to recognize it, but we were captured in one of the eyes.

503
01:14:31,000 --> 01:14:34,000
In the eyes episode, Bridge to Freedom".

504
01:14:34,000 --> 01:14:40,000
You see our bus pulling into Selma and innocent people.

505
01:14:40,000 --> 01:14:44,000
And I getting off the bus.

506
01:14:44,000 --> 01:14:52,000
But then after he turned us around, and we found out that a deal had been made,

507
01:14:52,000 --> 01:14:58,000
it did not enhance my view of Martin.

508
01:14:58,000 --> 01:15:06,000
It's only later in Atlanta with Benson listening, because Benson was an Albany with Martin.

509
01:15:06,000 --> 01:15:08,000
And he lived across...

510
01:15:08,000 --> 01:15:13,000
and also lived across the street from...

511
01:15:13,000 --> 01:15:18,000
Gladys Knight went to the church across the street from Benson's house.

512
01:15:18,000 --> 01:15:24,000
And Bernice Johnson Reagon lived on the first floor of Benson's house.

513
01:15:24,000 --> 01:15:27,000
But when Benson started...

514
01:15:27,000 --> 01:15:36,000
when we started researching, our initial project was to try and understand the movement

515
01:15:36,000 --> 01:15:39,000
that had just ended.

516
01:15:39,000 --> 01:15:45,000
When he started talking about Martin, and his relationship to Martin,

517
01:15:45,000 --> 01:15:50,000
the things Martin had done, and the things that Martin had been subjected to.

518
01:15:50,000 --> 01:15:56,000
And then later, when I started teaching on Martin and Malcolm X,

519
01:15:56,000 --> 01:16:02,000
and (David J.) Garrow's Bearing the Cross,

520
01:16:02,000 --> 01:16:09,000
I gained a greater admiration for Martin,

521
01:16:09,000 --> 01:16:16,000
because Martin was converging toward Malcolm X.

522
01:16:16,000 --> 01:16:23,000
There's a quote that I use and make it plain, that he makes six months before his assassination,

523
01:16:23,000 --> 01:16:29,000
where he says that everything he has been doing so far has been in vain.

524
01:16:29,000 --> 01:16:34,000
The whole thing has to be done away with.

525
01:16:34,000 --> 01:16:40,000
Dabba, dabba, dabba, do.

526
01:16:40,000 --> 01:16:46,000
So Martin, and that's the same disillusionment at least of Black Power.

527
01:16:46,000 --> 01:16:55,000
It's the same disillusionment that most of the movement people went through.

528
01:16:55,000 --> 01:17:02,000
When Malcolm X is attacked for being a hater and preaching violence,

529
01:17:02,000 --> 01:17:06,000
as I said, he was hard on Black people as he was on white people.

530
01:17:06,000 --> 01:17:10,000
But the critical question is not whether or not Malcolm X was a hater.

531
01:17:10,000 --> 01:17:19,000
The critical question is, why did tens of thousands and thousands more of Black men and women

532
01:17:19,000 --> 01:17:24,000
be sympathetic to Elijah Muhammad's description of the white man at the devil?

533
01:17:24,000 --> 01:17:26,000
That's the question.

534
01:17:26,000 --> 01:17:29,000
But America can't face itself.

535
01:17:29,000 --> 01:17:32,000
It can't face evil in its history.

536
01:17:32,000 --> 01:17:35,000
Everything it does is supposedly.

537
01:17:35,000 --> 01:17:39,000
So it talks about, again, to go back to the Lincoln example.

538
01:17:39,000 --> 01:17:41,000
Oh, yes, there was slavery here.

539
01:17:41,000 --> 01:17:42,000
There was a little blip.

540
01:17:42,000 --> 01:17:47,000
It's a little blip, unforeseen in blip in our history.

541
01:17:47,000 --> 01:17:53,000
But in 1860, America was the greatest slavehold in country and the history of the world.

542
01:17:53,000 --> 01:18:00,000
So when you start recontextualizing things, you draw much different conclusions.

543
01:18:00,000 --> 01:18:13,000
So I began to, after his death, and principally through Benson,

544
01:18:13,000 --> 01:18:19,000
until he researched, we did an IVW and subsequent research from my Malcolm X,

545
01:18:20,000 --> 01:18:25,000
and Martin, of course, I began to gain much more respect from Martin.

546
01:18:25,000 --> 01:18:28,000
If you just look here, one of the things that he and Malcolm X had in common,

547
01:18:28,000 --> 01:18:31,000
they were always on the road.

548
01:18:31,000 --> 01:18:36,000
And Martin had this whole responsibility to raise money for SCLC.

549
01:18:36,000 --> 01:18:43,000
And then the jealousy that he had to contain with.

550
01:18:43,000 --> 01:18:57,000
I began to appreciate it much more as a very, very significant distinguished, important person.

551
01:18:57,000 --> 01:19:00,000
Come up with some heart.

552
01:19:00,000 --> 01:19:05,000
Benson.

553
01:19:05,000 --> 01:19:11,000
I met Benson, who had, I think, my amulet while, for some kind of mini-conference,

554
01:19:11,000 --> 01:19:14,000
where we were on a panel together with First Man.

555
01:19:14,000 --> 01:19:17,000
And then we stayed in touch.

556
